Entry/stairs/cubby/copper Pico project.

Default pins:
- GPIO 14: reset button to GND, using internal pull-up
- GPIO 15: copper puzzle solved input
- GPIO 17: addressable cubby LED strip data
- GPIO 18: cubby 2 lock relay/driver input
- GPIO 19: optional copper puzzle begun input
- GPIO 6: laser distance sensor XSHUT
- GPIO 7: laser distance sensor GPIO1, reserved for future interrupt use
- I2C SDA/SCL: laser distance sensor SDA/SCL, usually GPIO 4/GPIO 5

MQTT publish:
- escape/puzzle/copper/begun
- escape/puzzle/copper/solved
- escape/puzzle/stairs/triggered

MQTT commands:
- escape/cubby/1/light_on
- escape/cubby/2/light_on
- escape/cubby/3/light_on
- escape/cubby/4/light_on
- escape/cubby/5/light_on
- escape/cubby/6/light_on
- escape/cubby/1/status
- escape/cubby/2/status
- escape/cubby/3/status
- escape/cubby/4/status
- escape/cubby/5/status
- escape/cubby/6/status
- escape/cubby/all/status
- escape/cubby/2/unlock
- escape/post/query
- escape/game/reset

MQTT POST publish:
- escape/post/cubby/1/state = ready or completed

Startup behavior:
- Pico sweeps the cubbies on in order.
- Pico holds all cubbies white for Raspberry Pi startup checks.
- Raspberry Pi queries puzzle states with escape/post/query.
- Raspberry Pi turns ready cubbies green and completed cubbies red.
- Raspberry Pi sends escape/cubby/all/status = off after all cubbies report ready.
- Pico clears the strip and waits for the stairs distance sensor.

Use a separate 5V supply for the cubby LED strip and share ground with the Pico.
Use relay, MOSFET, or isolated driver modules for locks and non-addressable powered lighting.
